Build it

00:00:08.830 --> 00:00:14.599
Gabriel Dishaw is making new art out of old
mechanical objects. He uses parts from typewriters,

00:00:14.599 --> 00:00:19.180
adding machines, and any old computers or
technology. His hope is to be able to continue

00:00:19.180 --> 00:00:24.500
to upcycle old items and help create a way
to deal with discarded technology. He has

00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:30.130
several different genres including a skull
series, table top sculptures, and figurative

00:00:30.130 --> 00:00:30.990
sculptures.

00:00:30.990 --> 00:00:36.500
Matthieu Georger makes these amazing and elaborate
Origami designs. Some of the designs are based

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:41.680
off of other renowned Origami artists and
some are of his own creation. He has hundreds

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:48.260
of these folded works of art including this
dragon, a centipede, buddha, and a minotaur.

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:52.830
Jeff Wright is a balloon artist who lives
in Bolivia doing charity work. He was challenged

00:00:52.830 --> 00:00:58.620
to make an Iron Man 3 balloon suit with less
than 500 balloons. He ended up finishing it

00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:03.730
in just under 10 hours and used 364 balloons.

00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:04.350
Draw it

00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:11.170
Mike Alcantara of comic collage art uses pieces
of old comics to recreate comic book heroes.

00:01:11.170 --> 00:01:16.180
All of his one-of-a-kind artworks are made
entirely of comics and they include Captain

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:20.240
America, The Joker, and Conan The Barbarian.&nbsp;

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:26.360
DJRoomba created Game of Thrones Sigils for
every NFL team. Many have multiple designs

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:33.030
such as the Buffalo's Bowed, Bent, Broken.
New England; By any means necessary, and San

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:37.000
Francisco Gold for our Glory, Red for Your
Blood.&nbsp;

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:52.070
And now for the Street Fighter chronicles
art from Arman Akopian...&nbsp;

00:01:52.070 --> 00:01:56.680
Photographer Joseph Ford made these clever
photos that mash up aerial landscapes with

00:01:56.680 --> 00:02:01.390
fashion photography. He used aerial images
he had previously shot and worked with an

00:02:01.390 --> 00:02:07.190
art director and stylist to come up with matching
fashion that would easily merge into the landscapes.

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:12.380
Some of the images took up to 12 hours to
match the fabrics and prints with the backgrounds.

